e are hopeful and they know that Nigerians are some of the most hard working people  some of the most resourceful people out there  that the government has been in the way  And therefore if they could only bring in a government that is interested and going to work for the people that their country is just going to go to good places  Hentz  The culture of corruption is persuasive  in Nigeria as it is in other countries  I think at some level  there s a level of if not acceptance of corruption  almost the notion that this is something we have to live with  And I ll give you an interesting anecdotal story  I was traveling back from the Niger Delta to the airport  and we were listening to the Nigerian radio  And they were reporting on the revelation that the president of the Philippines had  100 000 hidden in a bank account   I think the number was  100 000  The two Nigerian announcers started laughing and said   100 000  One of our governors would be embarrassed if they only had  100 000 in their bank account  And it was just the way they joked about it and laughed about it that made you realize that this is something that they deal with on a daily basis and you wonder if they re accepting it  not because they think it s right but because accepting that it s a part of their daily life  With the regions  with the traditional three regions    within each of those regions you have ethnic minorities which are very important  When Nigeria was formed it had three states  Gire  Three regions  Hentz  Three regions  it now has 36 states  and the proliferation of states over time was essentially a way to create what we call in political science  prebends  Prebends are the riches that come with holding office  the more offices you create  the more governorships you create   and I m not even talking about localities   I forget  what are there 180 something local governments  Every government structure you create  whether it s  a  state or what they call  a  locality  is another opportunity to attach prebends  wealth  patronage attached to the office  So not only is there an issue of corruption  there is an issue of institutionalized corruption over the last 30 or 40 years  Gire  That s a very important point  Jim  and I think I ll be more than happy to elaborate  to give you some interesting dimension to that  Yes  corruption has been around forever  in fact almost every military takeover  corruption was one of the reasons cited for the military taking over  but here s what has happened  To some extent it has been accepted by Nigerians as a way of life and so on  but it s a matter of magnitude  To give you a sense  it used to be that people who  say you are in charge of awarding contracts and so one and somebody bids for it you might cut some deal with someone to get 10 percent and that was viewed as a horrible thing  And then 10 percent went to maybe like 20 and 30  What has happened right now  which almost no Nigerian finds acceptable    an example will be somebody who holds office has a business partner that he favors and awards a contract maybe for a bridge  100 percent of the money for the bridge will be paid out and there will be no bridge  None  Certain rivers have had three or four bridges built across them that have never existed in reality  That s the current state  And even for Nigerians  that is too much  Which is why  Muhammadu  Buhari   is out there  Remember  a lot of the folks in the southwest are Christians  Buhari s running mate is an associate pastor of the Redeemed Church of Nigeria  OK  Buhari  when he went to Lagos a couple of months ago  laid out this challenge to Jonathan and every other Nigerian politician out there  He said   I was a military general and a head of state  I challenge anyone to bring to public any contracts that I may have given to myself or to anybody thought to be fronting for me  He said   I have no single foreign bank accounts  None  If you associate any bank account to my name that is not Nigeria